Third, the CVAT statistic can be derived from a multiple trait GBLUP model (or GFBLUP model)21, 22. This can be important if we have records on correlated traits, for example a high heritability trait (or a trait with many observations) correlated with a low heritability trait (or a trait with few observations). In such a situation using a multiple trait model is likely to increase the accuray of the predicted total genetic value and single marker effects for the low heritability trait which in turn will increase the power of the set test. This becomes highly relevant for borrowing information across traits or same trait recorded in different breeds or study populations. The linear mixed model for multiple traits (2 traits in this example) can be expressed as:11\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
